# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spatial-audio-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] 3-D audio (processing) is the spatial domain convolution of sound waves using head-related transfer functions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] It is the phenomenon of transforming sound waves (using head-related transfer function or HRTF filters and cross talk cancellation techniques) to mimic natural sounds waves, which emanate from a point in a 3-D space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] It allows trickery of the brain using the ears and auditory nerves, pretending to place different sounds in different 3-D locations upon hearing the sounds, even though the sounds may just be produced from only two speakers (dissimilar to surround sound).
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Using head-related transfer functions and reverberation, the changes of sound on its way from the source (including reflections from walls and floors) to the listener's ear can be simulated.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] These effects include localization of sound sources behind, above and below the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Some 3D technologies also convert binaural recordings to stereo recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] 3D Positional Audio effects emerged in the 1990s in PC and video game consoles.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] 3D audio techniques have also been incorporated in music and video-game style music video arts.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] True representation of the elevation level for 3D loudspeaker reproduction become possible by the Ambisonics and wave field synthesis (WFS) principle.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Some amusement parks have created attractions based around the principles of 3-D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] One example is *Sounds Dangerous!* at Disney's Hollywood Studios at the Walt Disney World Resort in Florida.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Guests wear special earphones as they watch a short film starring comedian Drew Carey.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] At a point in the film, the screen goes dark while a 3-D audio sound-track immerses the guests in the ongoing story.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] To ensure that the effect is heard properly, the earphone covers are color-coded to indicate how they should be worn.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] This is not a generated effect but a binaural recording.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Nick Cave's novel *The Death of Bunny Munro* was recorded in audiobook format using 3D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] The song "Propeller Seeds" by English artist Imogen Heap was recorded using 3D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] There have been developments in using 3D audio for DJ performances including the world's first Dolby Atmos event on 23 January 2016 held at Ministry of Sound, London.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] The event was a showcase of a 3D audio DJ set performed by Hospital Records owner Tony Colman aka London Elektricity.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] Other investigations included the Jago 3D Sound project which is looking at using Ambisonics combined with STEM music containers created and released by Native Instruments in 2015 for 3D nightclub sets.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] In November 2024 it was announced that the US Air Force had awarded a $9 million contract to Danish defense company Terma A/S, to supply its 3-D audio system for the F-16 Fighting Falcon aircraft, with a program of upgrades over the next two years.
[src:spatial-audio-games/3d-audio-effect] The system will provide high-fidelity digital audio by spatially separating radio signals, aligning audio with threat directions, and integrating active noise reduction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Unlike some other multichannel surround formats, its transmission channels do not carry speaker signals.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Instead, they contain a speaker-independent representation of a sound field called *B-format*, which is then *decoded* to the listener's speaker setup.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This extra step allows the producer to think in terms of source directions rather than loudspeaker positions, and offers the listener a considerable degree of flexibility as to the layout and number of speakers used for playback.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonics was developed in the UK in the 1970s under the auspices of the British National Research Development Corporation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Despite its solid technical foundation and many advantages, ambisonics had not until recently been a commercial success, and survived only in niche applications and among recording enthusiasts.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In particular, it has proved an effective way to present spatial audio in Virtual Reality applications (e.g.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] YouTube 360 Video), as the B-Format scene can be rotated to match the user's head orientation, and then be decoded as binaural stereo.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonics can be understood as a three-dimensional extension of M/S (mid/side) stereo, adding additional difference channels for height and depth.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The resulting signal set is called *B-format*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Its component channels are labelled W for the sound pressure (the M in M/S), X for the front-minus-back sound pressure gradient, Y for left-minus-right (the S in M/S) and Z for up-minus-down.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The W signal corresponds to an omnidirectional microphone, whereas $XYZ$ are the components that would be picked up by figure-of-eight capsules oriented along the three spatial axes.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A simple Ambisonic panner (or *encoder*) takes a source signal S and two parameters, the horizontal angle $\theta$ and the elevation angle $\phi$ .
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Being omnidirectional, the W channel always gets the same constant input signal, regardless of the angles.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] So that it has more-or-less the same average energy as the other channels, W is attenuated by about 3 dB (precisely, divided by the square root of two).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The terms for $XYZ$ actually produce the polar patterns of figure-of-eight microphones (see illustration on the right, second row).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] We take their value at $\theta$ and $\phi$ , and multiply the result with the input signal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The result is that the input ends up in all components exactly as loud as the corresponding microphone would have picked it up.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The B-format components can be combined to derive *virtual microphones* with any first-order polar pattern (omnidirectional, cardioid, hypercardioid, figure-of-eight or anything in between) pointing in any direction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Several such microphones with different parameters can be derived at the same time, to create coincident stereo pairs (such as a Blumlein) or surround arrays.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This virtual mic is *free-field normalised*, which means it has a constant gain of one for on-axis sounds.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The illustration on the left shows some examples created with this formula.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Virtual microphones can be manipulated in post-production: desired sounds can be picked out, unwanted ones suppressed, and the balance between direct and reverberant sound can be fine-tuned during mixing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A basic Ambisonic *decoder* is very similar to a set of virtual microphones.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] For perfectly regular layouts, a simplified decoder can be generated by pointing a virtual cardioid microphone in the direction of each speaker.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The signs of the X and Y components are the important part, the rest are gain factors.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Z component is discarded, because it is not possible to reproduce height cues with just four loudspeakers in one plane.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In practice, a real Ambisonic decoder requires a number of psycho-acoustic optimisations to work properly.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Currently, the All-Round Ambisonic Decoder (AllRAD) can be regarded as the standard solution for loudspeaker-based playback, and Magnitude Least Squares (MagLS) or binaural decoding, as implemented for instance in the IEM and SPARTA Ambisonic production tools.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Frequency-dependent decoding can also be used to produce binaural stereo; this is particularly relevant in Virtual Reality applications.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The spatial resolution of first-order ambisonics as described above is quite low.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In practice, that translates to slightly blurry sources, but also to a comparably small usable listening area or *sweet spot*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The resolution can be increased and the sweet spot enlarged by adding groups of more selective directional components to the B-format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] These no longer correspond to conventional microphone polar patterns, but rather look like clover leaves.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The resulting signal set is then called *second-*, *third-*, or collectively, *higher-order ambisonics*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] For a given order $\ell$ , full-sphere systems require $(\ell +1)^{2}$ signal components, and $2\ell +1$ components are needed for horizontal-only reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Historically there have been several different format conventions for higher-order ambisonics; for details see Ambisonic data exchange formats.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The B-format signals comprise a truncated spherical harmonic decomposition of the sound field.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] They correspond to the sound pressure W , and the three components of the pressure gradient $XYZ$ (not to be confused with the related particle velocity) at a point in space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Together, these approximate the sound field on a sphere around the microphone; formally the first-order truncation of the multipole expansion.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] W (the mono signal) is the zero-order information, corresponding to a constant function on the sphere, while $XYZ$ are the first-order terms (the dipoles or figures-of-eight).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This first-order truncation is only an approximation of the overall sound field.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The *higher orders* correspond to further terms of the multipole expansion of a function on the sphere in terms of spherical harmonics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In practice, higher orders require more speakers for playback, but increase the spatial resolution and enlarge the area where the sound field is reproduced perfectly (up to an upper boundary frequency).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This area becomes smaller than a human head above 600 Hz for first order or 1800 Hz for third-order.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Accurate reproduction in a head-sized volume up to 20 kHz would require an order of 32 or more than 1000 loudspeakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] At those frequencies and listening positions where perfect soundfield reconstruction is no longer possible, ambisonics reproduction has to focus on delivering correct directional cues to allow for good localisation even in the presence of reconstruction errors.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The human hearing apparatus has very keen localisation on the horizontal plane (as fine as 2° source separation in some experiments).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] At low frequencies, where the wavelength is large compared to the human head, an incoming sound diffracts around it, so that there is virtually no acoustic shadow and hence no level difference between the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In this range, the only available information is the phase relationship between the two ear signals, called *interaural time difference*, or *ITD*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Evaluating this time difference allows for precise localisation within a *cone of confusion*: the angle of incidence is unambiguous, but the ITD is the same for sounds from the front or from the back.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] As long as the sound is not totally unknown to the subject, the confusion can usually be resolved by perceiving the timbral front-back variations caused by the ear flaps (or *pinnae*).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] As the wavelength approaches twice the size of the head, phase relationships become ambiguous, since it is no longer clear whether the phase difference between the ears corresponds to one, two, or even more periods as the frequency goes up.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Fortunately, the head will create a significant acoustic shadow in this range, which causes a slight difference in level between the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This is called the *interaural level difference*, or *ILD* (the same cone of confusion applies).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Combined, these two mechanisms provide localisation over the entire hearing range.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Gerzon has shown that the quality of localisation cues in the reproduced sound field corresponds to two objective metrics: the length of the particle velocity vector ${\vec {r_{V}}}$ for the ITD, and the length of the energy vector ${\vec {r_{E}}}$ for the ILD.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In practice, satisfactory results are achieved at moderate orders even for very large listening areas.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Humans are also able to derive information about sound source location in 3D-space, taking into account height.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Much of this ability is due to the shape of the head (especially the pinna) producing a variable frequency response depending on the angle of the source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The response can be measured by placing a microphone in a person's ear canal, then playing back sounds from various directions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The recorded head-related transfer function (HRTF) can then be used for rendering ambisonics to headphones, mimicking the effect of the head.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] HRTFs differ among person to person due to head shape variations, but a generic one can produce a satisfactory result.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In principle, the loudspeaker signals are derived by using a linear combination of the Ambisonic component signals, where each signal is dependent on the actual position of the speaker in relation to the center of an imaginary sphere the surface of which passes through all available speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In practice, slightly irregular distances of the speakers may be compensated with delay.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] True ambisonics decoding however requires spatial equalisation of the signals to account for the differences in the high- and low-frequency sound localisation mechanisms in human hearing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A further refinement accounts for the distance of the listener from the loudspeakers (*near-field compensation*).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A variety of more modern decoding methods are also in use.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonics decoders are not currently being marketed to end users in any significant way, and no native Ambisonic recordings are commercially available.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Hence, content that has been produced in ambisonics must be made available to consumers in stereo or discrete multichannel formats.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonics content can be folded down to stereo automatically, without requiring a dedicated downmix.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The most straightforward approach is to sample the B-format with a *virtual stereo microphone*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The result is equivalent to a coincident stereo recording.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Imaging will depend on the microphone geometry, but usually rear sources will be reproduced more softly and diffuse.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Vertical information (from the Z channel) is omitted.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Alternatively, the B-format can be matrix-encoded into *UHJ format*, which is suitable for direct playback on stereo systems.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] As before, the vertical information will be discarded, but in addition to left-right reproduction, UHJ tries to retain some of the horizontal surround information by translating sources in the back into out-of-phase signals.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This gives the listener some sense of rear localisation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Two-channel UHJ can also be decoded back into horizontal ambisonics (with some loss of accuracy), if an Ambisonic playback system is available.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Lossless UHJ up to four channels (including height information) exists but has never seen wide use.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In all UHJ schemes, the first two channels are conventional left and right speaker feeds.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Likewise, it is possible to pre-decode ambisonics material to arbitrary speaker layouts, such as Quad, 5.1, 7.1, Auro 11.1, or even 22.2, again without manual intervention.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The LFE channel is either omitted, or a special mix is created manually.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Pre-decoding to 5.1 media has been known as *G-Format* during the early days of DVD audio, although the term is not in common use anymore.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The obvious advantage of pre-decoding is that any surround listener can be able to experience ambisonics; no special hardware is required beyond that found in a common home theatre system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The main disadvantage is that the flexibility of rendering a single, standard ambisonics signal to any target speaker array is lost: the signal is assumes a specific "standard" layout and anyone listening with a different array may experience a degradation of localisation accuracy.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Target layouts from 5.1 upwards usually surpass the spatial resolution of first-order ambisonics, at least in the frontal quadrant.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] For optimal resolution, to avoid excessive crosstalk, and to steer around irregularities of the target layout, pre-decodings for such targets should be derived from source material in higher-order ambisonics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonic content can be created in two basic ways: by recording a sound with a suitable first- or higher-order microphone, or by taking separate monophonic sources and panning them to the desired positions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Content can also be manipulated while it is in B-format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This is referred to as a *native* or *Nimbus/Halliday* microphone array, after its designer Dr Jonathan Halliday at Nimbus Records, where it is used to record their extensive and continuing series of Ambisonic releases.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] An integrated native B-format microphone, the C700S has been manufactured and sold by Josephson Engineering since 1990.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The primary difficulty inherent in this approach is that high-frequency localisation and clarity relies on the diaphragms approaching true coincidence.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] By stacking the capsules vertically, perfect coincidence for horizontal sources is obtained.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] However, sound from above or below will theoretically suffer from subtle comb filtering effects in the highest frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In most instances this is not a limitation as sound sources far from the horizontal plane are typically from room reverberation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In addition, stacked figure-8 microphone elements have a deep null in the direction of their stacking axis such that the primary transducer in those directions is the central omnidirectional microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Native arrays are most commonly used for horizontal-only surround, because of increasing positional errors and shading effects when adding a fourth microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Since it is impossible to build a perfectly coincident microphone array, the next-best approach is to minimize and distribute the positional error as uniformly as possible.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This can be achieved by arranging four cardioid or sub-cardioid capsules in a tetrahedron and equalising for uniform diffuse-field response.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The capsule signals are then converted to B-format with a matrix operation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Core Sound TetraMic was the first commercially available A-format ambisonic microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Introduced in 2006, it uses four cardioid capsules.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Each TetraMic is individually calibrated, and a calibration file and A- to B-format encoder plug-in are provided with each microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Outside ambisonics, tetrahedral microphones have become popular with location recording engineers working in stereo or 5.1 for their flexibility in post-production; here, the B-format is only used as an intermediate to derive virtual microphones.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Above first-order, it is no longer possible to obtain Ambisonic components directly with single microphone capsules.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Instead, higher-order difference signals are derived from several spatially distributed (usually omnidirectional) capsules using very sophisticated digital signal processing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Core Sound OctoMic was the first commercially available second-order ambisonic microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Introduced in 2018, it uses eight cardioid capsules.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Each OctoMic is individually calibrated, and a calibration file and A- to B-format encoder plug-in are provided with each microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The ZYLIA ZM-1 is a commercially available microphone capable of generating third-order ambisonic recordings, using 19 omni-directional capsules.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The em64 Eigenmike from mh acoustics is a 64-channel spherical microphone array capable of sixth-order capture.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The production of the em64 has superseded their previous em32 microphone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The spacemic from Harpex Audio GmbH is an 84-channel double-sided planar array.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Current versions of its encoder as of late 2025 support fifth-order spherical capture.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] (subsequently patented) describes the use of bi-directional capsules for higher order microphones to reduce the extremity of the equalisation involved.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] No microphones have yet been made using this idea.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The most straightforward way to produce Ambisonic mixes of arbitrarily high order is to take monophonic sources and position them with an Ambisonic encoder.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A full-sphere encoder usually has two parameters, azimuth (or horizon) and elevation angle.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The encoder will distribute the source signal to the Ambisonic components such that, when decoded, the source will appear at the desired location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] More sophisticated panners will additionally provide a radius parameter that will take care of distance-dependent attenuation and bass boost due to near-field effect.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Hardware panning units and mixers for first-order ambisonics have been available since the 1980s and have been used commercially.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Today, panning plugins and other related software tools are available for all major digital audio workstations, often as free software.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] However, due to arbitrary bus width restrictions, few professional digital audio workstations (DAW) support orders higher than second.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Notable exceptions are REAPER, Pyramix, ProTools, Nuendo and Ardour.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] First order B-format can be manipulated in various ways to change the contents of an auditory scene.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Well known manipulations include "rotation" and "dominance" (moving sources towards or away from a particular direction).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Additionally, linear time-invariant signal processing such as equalisation can be applied to B-format without disrupting sound directions, as long as it applied to all component channels equally.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] More recent developments in higher order ambisonics enable a wide range of manipulations including rotation, reflection, movement, 3D reverb, upmixing from legacy formats such as 5.1 or first order, visualisation and directionally-dependent masking and equalisation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Transmitting Ambisonic B-format between devices and to end-users requires a standardized exchange format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] While *traditional first-order B-format* is well-defined and universally understood, there are conflicting conventions for higher-order ambisonics, differing both in channel order and weighting, which might need to be supported for some time.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Traditionally, the *Furse-Malham (FuMa) higher order format* in the `.amb` container based on Microsoft's WAVE-EX file format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] It scales up to third order and has a file size limitation of 4GB.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The current B-format standard format is AmbiX proposal, which adopts the `.caf` file format and does away with the 4GB limit.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] It scales to arbitrarily high orders and is based on SN3D encoding.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] SN3D encoding has been adopted by Google as the basis for its YouTube 360 format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] To effectively distribute Ambisonic data to non-professionals, lossy compression is desired to keep the data size acceptable.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] However, simple multi-mono compression is not sufficient, as lossy compression tends to destroy phase information and thus degrade localization in the form of spatial reduction, blur, and phantom source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Reduction of redundancy among channels is desired, not only to enhance compression, but also to reduce the risk of discernable phase errors.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] As with mid-side joint stereo encoding, a static matrixing scheme (as in Opus) is usable for first-order ambisonics, but not optimal in case of multiple sources.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A number of schemes such as DirAC use a scheme similar to parametric stereo, where a downmixed signal is encoded, the principal direction recorded, and some description of ambiance added.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] MPEG-H 3D Audio, drawing on some work from MPEG Surround, extends the concept to handle multiple sources.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] MPEG-H uses principal component analysis to determine the main sources and then encodes a multi-mono signal corresponding to the principal directions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] These parametric methods provide good quality, so long as they take good care in smoothing sound directions among frames.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] PCA/SVD is applicable for first-order as well as high-order ambisonics input.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This section focusses on decoding of classic first-order ambisonics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Ambisonic B-format WXYZ signals define what the listener should hear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] How these signals are presented to the listener by the speakers for best results, depends on the number of speakers and their location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ambisonics treats directions where no speakers are placed with as much importance as speaker positions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] It is undesirable for the listener to be conscious that the sound is coming from a discrete number of speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Some simple decoding equations are known to give good results for common speaker arrangements.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] But Ambisonic Speaker Decoders can use much more information about the position of speakers, including their exact position and distance from the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Because human beings use different mechanisms to locate sound, **Classic Ambisonic Decoders** it is desirable to modify the speaker feeds at each frequency to present the best information using Shelf Filters.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Some views on the complexities of **Shelf Filters** and **Distance Compensation** are explained in "Ambisonic Surround Decoders" and "SHELF FILTERS for Ambisonic Decoders".
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] There are specialised decoders for large audiences in large spaces.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Hardware decoders have been commercially available since the late 1970s; currently, ambisonics is standard in surround products offered by Meridian Audio, Ltd.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ad hoc software decoders are also available.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This design is intended for a domestic, small room setting, and allows speakers to be arranged in diametrically opposed pairs.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This design is intended for a domestic, small room setting.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The speakers are equidistant from the listener and lie equally spaced on the circumference of a circle.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The simplest Regular Polygon decoder is a Square with the listener in the centre.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Triangles do not work, exhibiting large "holes" between the speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Regular Hexagons perform better than Squares especially to the sides.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] where $\theta _{n}$ is the direction of the speaker under consideration.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The most useful of these is the Square 4.0 decoder.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The coordinate system used in ambisonics follows the right hand rule convention with positive X pointing forwards, positive Y pointing to the left and positive Z pointing upwards.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Horizontal angles run anticlockwise from due front and vertical angles are positive above the horizontal, negative below.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This design is intended for a large, public space setting.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] These are so named because the paper introducing deriving Ambisonic Decoders for irregular loudspeaker layouts was presented at the 1992 AES conference held in Vienna.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The design was covered by a 1998 patent. from Trifield Productions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The technology provides one approach to the decoding of ambisonic signals to irregular loudspeaker arrays (such as ITU) commonly used for 5.1 surround sound replay.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The idea behind parametric decoding is to treat the sound's direction of incidence as a parameter that can be estimated through time–frequency analysis.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A large body of research into human spatial hearing suggests that our auditory cortex applies similar techniques in its auditory scene analysis, which explains why these methods work.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The major benefit of parametric decoding is a greatly increased angular resolution and the separation of analysis and synthesis into separate processing steps.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] This separation allows B-format recordings to be rendered using any panning technique, including delay panning, VBAP and HRTF-based synthesis.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Parametric decoding was pioneered by Lake DSP in the late 1990s and independently suggested by Farina and Ugolotti in 1999.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Later work in this domain includes the DirAC method and the Harpex method.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Rapture3D decoder from Blue Ripple Sound supports this and is already used in a number of computer games using OpenAL.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Since 2018 a free and open source implementation exists in the IEM Plugin Suite and the SPARTA suite that implement the recent academic developments and the sound codec Opus.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Opus provides two channel encoding modes: one that simply stores channels individually, and another that weights the channels through a fixed, invertible matrix to reduce redundancy.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] A listening-test of Opus ambisonics was published in 2020, as calibration for AMBIQUAL, an objective metric for compressed ambisonics by Google.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Opus third-order ambisonics at 256 kbps has similar localization accuracy compared to Opus first-order ambisonics at 128 kbps.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Since its adoption by Google and other manufacturers as the audio format of choice for virtual reality, ambisonics has seen a surge of interest.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] In 2018, Sennheiser released its VR microphone, and Zoom released an Ambisonics Field Recorder.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Both are implementations of the tetrahedral microphone design which produces first order ambisonics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Atmos takes a fundamentally different approach in that it does not attempt to transmit a sound field; it transmits discrete premixes or stems (i.e., raw streams of sound data) along with metadata about what location and direction they should appear to be coming from.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The stems are then decoded, mixed, and rendered in real time using whatever loudspeakers are available at the playback location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Higher-order ambisonics has found a niche market in video games developed by Codemasters.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Their first game to use an Ambisonic audio engine was Colin McRae: DiRT, however, this only used ambisonics on the PlayStation 3 platform.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Their game Race Driver: GRID extended the use of ambisonics to the Xbox 360 platform, and Colin McRae: DiRT 2 uses ambisonics on all platforms including the PC.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The recent games from Codemasters, F1 2010, Dirt 3, F1 2011 and Dirt: Showdown, use fourth-order ambisonics on faster PCs, rendered by Blue Ripple Sound's Rapture3D OpenAL driver and pre-mixed Ambisonic audio produced using Bruce Wiggins' WigWare Ambisonic Plug-ins.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] OpenAL Soft , a free and open source implementation of the OpenAL specification, also uses ambisonics to render 3D audio.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] OpenAL Soft can often be used as a drop-in replacement for other OpenAL implementations, enabling several games that use the OpenAL API to benefit from rendering audio with ambisonics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] For many games that do not make use of the OpenAL API natively, the use of a wrapper or a chain of wrappers can help to make these games indirectly use the OpenAL API.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Ultimately, this leads to the sound being rendered in ambisonics if a capable OpenAL driver such as OpenAL Soft is being used.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Unreal Engine supports soundfield ambisonics rendering since version 4.25.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The Unity engine supports working with ambisonics audio clips since version 2017.1.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] Most of the patents covering Ambisonic developments have now expired (including those covering the Soundfield microphone) and, as a result, the basic technology is available for anyone to implement.
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The system was ultimately licensed to Nimbus Records (now owned by Wyastone Estate Ltd).
[src:spatial-audio-games/ambisonics] The "interlocking circles" Ambisonic logo (UK trademarks UK00001113276 and UK00001113277), and the text marks "AMBISONIC" and "A M B I S O N" (UK trademarks UK00001500177 and UK00001112259), formerly owned by Wyastone Estate Ltd., have expired as of 2010.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] A **head-related transfer function** (**HRTF**) is a response that characterizes how an ear receives a sound from a point in space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] As sound strikes the listener, the size and shape of the head, ears, ear canal, density of the head, size and shape of nasal and oral cavities, all transform the sound and affect how it is perceived, boosting some frequencies and attenuating others.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Generally speaking, the HRTF boosts frequencies from 2–5 kHz with a primary resonance of +17 dB at 2,700 Hz.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] But the response curve is more complex than a single bump, affects a broad frequency spectrum, and varies significantly from person to person.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] A pair of HRTFs for two ears can be used to synthesize a binaural sound that seems to come from a particular point in space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] It is a transfer function, describing how a sound from a specific point will arrive at the ear (generally at the outer end of the auditory canal).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Some consumer home entertainment products designed to reproduce surround sound from stereo (two-speaker) headphones use HRTFs.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Some forms of HRTF processing have also been included in computer software to simulate surround sound playback from loudspeakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Humans have just two ears, but can locate sounds in three dimensions – in range (distance), in direction above and below (elevation), in front and to the rear, as well as to either side (azimuth).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This is possible because the brain, inner ear, and the external ears (pinna) work together to make inferences about location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Humans estimate the location of a source by taking cues derived from one ear (*monaural cues*), and by comparing cues received at both ears (*difference cues* or *binaural cues*).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Among the difference cues are time differences of arrival and intensity differences.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The monaural cues come from the interaction between the sound source and the human anatomy, in which the original source sound is modified before it enters the ear canal for processing by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] These modifications encode the source location and may be captured via an impulse response which relates the source location and the ear location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This impulse response is termed the *head-related impulse response* (HRIR).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Convolution of an arbitrary source sound with the HRIR converts the sound to that which would have been heard by the listener if it had been played at the source location, with the listener's ear at the receiver location.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] HRIRs have been used to produce virtual surround sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF is the Fourier transform of HRIR.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs for left and right ear (expressed above as HRIRs) describe the filtering of a sound source (*x*(*t*)) before it is perceived at the left and right ears as *x*L(*t*) and *x*R(*t*), respectively.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF can also be described as the modifications to a sound from a direction in free air to the sound as it arrives at the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] These modifications include the shape of the listener's outer ear, the shape of the listener's head and body, the acoustic characteristics of the space in which the sound is played, and so on.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] All these characteristics will influence how (or whether) a listener can accurately tell what direction a sound is coming from.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] In the AES69-2015 standard, the Audio Engineering Society (AES) has defined the SOFA file format for storing spatially oriented acoustic data like head-related transfer functions (HRTFs).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] SOFA software libraries and files are collected at the Sofa Conventions website.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The associated mechanism varies between individuals, as their head and ear shapes differ.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] HRTF describes how a given sound wave input (parameterized as frequency and source location) is filtered by the diffraction and reflection properties of the head, pinna, and torso, before the sound reaches the transduction machinery of the eardrum and inner ear (see auditory system).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Biologically, the source-location-specific prefiltering effects of these external structures aid in the neural determination of source location, particularly the determination of the source's elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Linear systems analysis defines the transfer function as the complex ratio between the output signal spectrum and the input signal spectrum as a function of frequency.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Blauert (1974; cited in Blauert, 1981) initially defined the transfer function as the free-field transfer function (FFTF).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Other terms include free-field to eardrum transfer function and the pressure transformation from the free-field to the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Less specific descriptions include the pinna transfer function, the outer ear transfer function, the pinna response, or directional transfer function (DTF).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] One method used to obtain the HRTF from a given source location is therefore to measure the head-related impulse response (HRIR), *h*(*t*), at the ear drum for the impulse *Δ*(*t*) placed at the source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF *H*(*f*) is the Fourier transform of the HRIR *h*(*t*).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Even when measured for a "dummy head" of idealized geometry, HRTF are complicated functions of frequency and the three spatial variables.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] For distances greater than 1 m from the head, however, the HRTF can be said to attenuate inversely with range.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] It is this far field HRTF, *H*(*f*, *θ*, *φ*), that has most often been measured.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] At closer range, the difference in level observed between the ears can grow quite large, even in the low-frequency region within which negligible level differences are observed in the far field.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs are typically measured in an anechoic chamber to minimize the influence of early reflections and reverberation on the measured response.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] HRTFs are measured at small increments of *θ* such as 15° or 30° in the horizontal plane, with interpolation used to synthesize *HRTF*s for arbitrary positions of *θ*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Even with small increments, however, interpolation can lead to front-back confusion, and optimizing the interpolation procedure is an active area of research.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] In order to maximize the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) in a measured HRTF, it is important that the impulse being generated be of high volume.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] In practice, however, it can be difficult to generate impulses at high volumes and, if generated, they can be damaging to human ears, so it is more common for HRTFs to be directly calculated in the frequency domain using a frequency-swept sine wave or by using maximum length sequences.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] User fatigue is still a problem, however, highlighting the need for the ability to interpolate based on fewer measurements.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The head-related transfer function is involved in resolving the cone of confusion, a series of points where interaural time difference (ITD) and interaural level difference (ILD) are identical for sound sources from many locations around the *0* part of the cone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] When a sound is received by the ear it can either go straight down the ear into the ear canal or it can be reflected off the pinnae of the ear, into the ear canal a fraction of a second later.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Essentially, the brain is looking for frequency notches in the signal that correspond to particular known directions of sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] If another person's ears were substituted, the individual would not immediately be able to localize sound, as the patterns of enhancement and cancellation would be different from those patterns the person's auditory system is used to.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] However, after some weeks, the auditory system would adapt to the new head-related transfer function.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The inter-subject variability in the spectra of HRTFs has been studied through cluster analyses.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Assessing the variation through changes between the person's ear, we can limit our perspective with the degrees of freedom of the head and its relation with the spatial domain.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Through this, we eliminate the tilt and other co-ordinate parameters that add complexity.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] For the purpose of calibration we are only concerned with the direction level to our ears, ergo a specific degree of freedom.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] A basic assumption in the creation of a virtual auditory space is that if the acoustical waveforms present at a listener's eardrums are the same under headphones as in free field, then the listener's experience should also be the same.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Typically, sounds generated from headphones are perceived as originating from within the head.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] In the virtual auditory space, the headphones should be able to "externalize" the sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Using the HRTF, sounds can be spatially positioned using the technique described below.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Let *x*1(*t*) represent an electrical signal driving a loudspeaker and *y*1(*t*) represent the signal received by a microphone inside the listener's eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Similarly, let *x*2(*t*) represent the electrical signal driving a headphone and *y*2(*t*) represent the microphone response to the signal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The goal of the virtual auditory space is to choose *x*2(*t*) such that *y*2(*t*) = *y*1(*t*).
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] where *L* is the transfer function of the loudspeaker in the free field, *F* is the HRTF, *M* is the microphone transfer function, and *H* is the headphone-to-eardrum transfer function.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Therefore, theoretically, if *x*1(*t*) is passed through this filter and the resulting *x*2(*t*) is played on the headphones, it should produce the same signal at the eardrum.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Since the filter applies only to a single ear, another one must be derived for the other ear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This process is repeated for many places in the virtual environment to create an array of head-related transfer functions for each position to be recreated while ensuring that the sampling conditions are set by the Nyquist criteria.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] There is less reliable phase estimation in the very low part of the frequency band, and in the upper frequencies the phase response is affected by the features of the pinna.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Earlier studies also show that the HRTF phase response is mostly linear and that listeners are insensitive to the details of the interaural phase spectrum as long as the interaural time delay (ITD) of the combined low-frequency part of the waveform is maintained.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This is the modeled phase response of the subject HRTF as a time delay, dependent on the direction and elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] A scaling factor is a function of the anthropometric features.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] For example, a training set of N subjects would consider each HRTF phase and describe a single ITD scaling factor as the average delay of the group.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This computed scaling factor can estimate the time delay as function of the direction and elevation for any given individual.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Converting the time delay to phase response for the left and the right ears is trivial.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF phase can be described by the ITD scaling factor.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] This is in turn quantified by the anthropometric data of a given individual taken as the source of reference.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] that represents the subject's anthropometric features as a linear superposition of the anthropometric features from the training data (y' = βT X), and then apply the same sparse vector directly on the scaling vector H.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] where The ITD scaling factors for all persons in the dataset are stacked in a vector *H* ∈ ***R****N*, so the value *H**n* corresponds to the scaling factor of the n-th person.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] We solve the above minimization problem using least absolute shrinkage and selection operator.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] We assume that the HRTFs are represented by the same relation as the anthropometric features.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] where The HRTFs for each subject are described by a tensor of size *D* × *K*, where *D* is the number of HRTF directions and *K* is the number of frequency bins.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] All *H**n*,*d*,*k* corresponds to all the HRTFs of the training set are stacked in a new tensor *H* ∈ ***R****N*×*D*×*K*, so the value Hn,d,k corresponds to the *k*-th frequency bin for *d*-th HRTF direction of the *n*-th person.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Also *H*'*d*,*k* corresponds to *k*-th frequency for every d-th HRTF direction of the synthesized HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Accumulation of HRTF data has made it possible for a computer program to infer an approximate HRTF from head geometry.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Two programs are known to do so, both open-source: Mesh2HRTF, which runs physical simulation on a full 3D-mesh of the head, and EAC, which uses a neural network trained from existing HRTFs and works from photo and other rough measurements.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The perceived accuracy of the result depends on how closely the HRTF data set matches the characteristics of one's own ears, though a generic HRTF may be preferred to an accurate one measured from one's one ear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Some vendors like Apple and Sony offer a variety of HRTFs to be selected by the user's ear shape.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Windows 10 and above come with Microsoft Spatial Sound included, the same spatial audio framework used on Xbox One and Hololens 2.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] On a Windows PC or an Xbox One, the framework can use several different downstream audio processors, including Windows Sonic for Headphones, Dolby Atmos, and DTS Headphone:X, to apply an HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The framework can render both fixed-position surround sound sources and dynamic "object" sources that can move in space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Apple similarly has Spatial Sound for its devices used with headphones produced by Apple or Beats.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] For music playback to headphones, Dolby Atmos can be enabled and the HRTF applied.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The HRTF (or rather, the object positions) can vary with head tracking to maintain the illusion of direction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Qualcomm Snapdragon has a similar head-tracked spatial audio system, used by some brands of Android phones.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] YouTube uses head-tracked HRTF with 360-degree and VR videos.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Linux is currently unable to directly process any of the proprietary spatial audio (surround plus dynamic objects) formats.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] SoundScape Renderer offers directional synthesis.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] PulseAudio and PipeWire each can provide virtual surround (fixed-location channels) using an HRTF.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Recent PipeWire versions are also able to provide dynamic spatial rendering using HRTFs, however integration with applications is still in progress.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Users can configure their own positional and dynamic sound sources, as well as simulate a surround speaker setup using existing configurations.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] The cross-platform OpenAL Soft, an implementation of OpenAL, uses HRTFs for improved localization.
[src:spatial-audio-games/head-related-transfer-function] Windows and Linux spatial audio systems support any model of stereo headphones, while Apple only allows spatial audio to be used with Apple or Beats-branded Bluetooth headsets.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] While the reference implementation later became proprietary and unmaintained, there are open source implementations such as OpenAL Soft available.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] OpenAL was originally developed in 2000 by Loki Software to help them in their business of porting Windows games to Linux.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] After the demise of Loki, the project was maintained for a time by the free software/open source community, and implemented on NVIDIA nForce sound cards and motherboards.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] It was hosted (and largely developed) by Creative Technology until circa 2012.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Since 1.1 (2009), the sample implementation by Creative has turned proprietary, with the last releases in free licenses still accessible through the project's Subversion source code repository.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] However, OpenAL Soft is a widely used open source alternative and remains actively maintained and extended.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] While the OpenAL charter says that there will be an "Architecture Review Board" (ARB) modeled on the OpenGL ARB, no such organization has ever been formed and the OpenAL specification is generally handled and discussed via email on its public mailing list.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The original mailing list, openal-devel hosted by Creative, ran from March 2003 to circa August 2012.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Gordon, a Loki veteran who went on to develop Simple DirectMedia Layer, started a new mailing list and website at OpenAL.org in January 2014.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] As of February 2023, the list remains in use.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The general functionality of OpenAL is encoded in *source objects*, *audio buffers* and a single *listener*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] A source object contains a pointer to a buffer, the velocity, position and direction of the sound, and the intensity of the sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The listener object contains the velocity, position and direction of the listener, and the general gain applied to all sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Buffers contain audio data in PCM format, either 8- or 16-bit, in either monaural or stereo format.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The rendering engine performs all necessary calculations for distance attenuation, Doppler effect, etc.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The net result of all of this for the end user is that in a properly written OpenAL application, sounds behave quite naturally as the user moves through the three-dimensional space of the virtual world.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] From a programmer's perspective, very little additional work is required to make this happen in an existing OpenGL-based 3D graphical application.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Unlike the OpenGL specification, the OpenAL specification includes two subsections of the API: the core consisting of the actual OpenAL function calls, and the ALC (Audio Library Context) API which is used to manage rendering contexts, resource usage and locking in a cross platform manner.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] There is also an 'ALUT' (Audio Library Utility Toolkit) library that provides higher level 'convenience' functions — exactly analogous to OpenGL's 'GLUT'.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] In order to provide additional functionality in the future, OpenAL utilizes an extension mechanism.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Individual vendors are thereby able to include their own extensions into distributions of OpenAL, commonly for the purpose of exposing additional functionality on their proprietary hardware.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Extensions can be promoted to ARB (Architecture Review Board) status, indicating a standard extension which will be maintained for backwards compatibility.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] ARB extensions have the prospect of being added to the core API after a period of time.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] For advanced digital signal processing and hardware-accelerated sound effects, the EFX (Effects Extension) or environmental audio extensions (EAX) can be used.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The *single listener* model in OpenAL is tailored to a single human user and is not fit for artificial intelligence or robotic simulations or multiple human participants as in collaborative musical performances.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] In these cases a multiple listener model is required.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] OpenAL also fails to take into account *sound propagation delays* (the speed of sound is used for the Doppler effect only).
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The distance to a sound source only translates into an amplitude effect (attenuation) and not a delay.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Hence OpenAL cannot be used for time difference of arrival calculations unless that functionality is added in separately.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] In order to take full speed advantage of OpenAL, a vendor/hardware specific implementation is needed and these are seldom released as open source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Many supported platforms in fact implement OpenAL as a wrapper which simply translates calls to the platform's native, and often proprietary, audio API.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Supported gaming devices are for instance: GameCube, PlayStation 2, PlayStation 3, Xbox, Xbox 360, Wii, and PlayStation Portable.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The OpenAL Sample Implementation is the original implementation, from Loki, and is not currently maintained.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] OpenAL Soft is an LGPL-licensed, cross-platform, software implementation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The library is meant as a free compatible update/replacement to the now-deprecated and proprietary OpenAL Sample Implementation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] OpenAL Soft supports mono, stereo (including HRTF and UHJ), 4-channel, 5.1, 6.1, 7.1, and B-Format output.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] library this implementation supports HRTF as well as spatialised surround sound for up to eight speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] The library is intended as a high performance drop-in replacement for other implementations.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] Apple ships an implementation of OpenAL in macOS and iOS.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] It is a very thin layer over the 3D Mixer (kAudioUnitSubType_3DMixer) feature in the operating system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/openal] This implementation was originally written by Ryan C.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] In acoustics, **reverberation** (commonly shortened to **reverb**) is a persistence of sound after it is produced.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] It is often created when a sound is reflected on surfaces, causing multiple reflections that build up and then decay as the sound is absorbed by the surfaces of objects in the space – which could include furniture, people, and air.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This is most noticeable when the sound source stops but the reflections continue, their amplitude decreasing, until zero is reached.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation is frequency dependent: the length of the decay, or reverberation time, receives special consideration in the architectural design of spaces which need to have specific reverberation times to achieve optimum performance for their intended activity.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] In comparison to a distinct echo, that is detectable at a minimum of 50 to 100 ms after the previous sound, reverberation is the occurrence of reflections that arrive in a sequence of less than approximately 50 ms.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] As time passes, the amplitude of the reflections gradually reduces to non-noticeable levels.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation is not limited to indoor spaces as it exists in forests and other outdoor environments where reflection exists.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation occurs naturally when a person sings, talks, or plays an instrument acoustically in a hall or performance space with sound-reflective surfaces.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation is applied artificially by using reverb effects, which simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Although reverberation can add naturalness to recorded sound by adding a sense of space, it can also reduce speech intelligibility, especially when noise is also present.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] People with hearing loss, including users of hearing aids, frequently report difficulty in understanding speech in reverberant, noisy situations.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation is also a significant source of mistakes in automatic speech recognition.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] When it comes to accurately measuring reverberation time with a meter, the term *T60* (an abbreviation for reverberation time 60 dB) is used.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] T60 provides an objective reverberation time measurement.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] It is defined as the time it takes for the sound pressure level to reduce by 60 dB, measured after the generated test signal is abruptly ended.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation time is frequently stated as a single value if measured as a wideband signal (20 Hz to 20 kHz).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] However, being frequency-dependent, it can be more precisely described in terms of frequency bands (one octave, 1/3 octave, 1/6 octave, etc.).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Being frequency dependent, the reverberation time measured in narrow bands will differ depending on the frequency band being measured.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] For precision, it is important to know what ranges of frequencies are being described by a reverberation time measurement.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] In the late 19th century, Wallace Clement Sabine started experiments at Harvard University to investigate the impact of absorption on the reverberation time.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Using a portable wind chest and organ pipes as a sound source, a stopwatch and his ears, he measured the time from interruption of the source to inaudibility (a difference of roughly 60 dB).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] He found that the reverberation time is proportional to room dimensions and inversely proportional to the amount of absorption present.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The optimum reverberation time for a space in which music is played depends on the type of music that is to be played in the space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Rooms used for speech typically need a shorter reverberation time so that speech can be understood more clearly.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] If the reflected sound from one syllable is still heard when the next syllable is spoken, it may be difficult to understand what was said.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] "Cat", "cab", and "cap" may all sound very similar.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] If on the other hand the reverberation time is too short, tonal balance and loudness may suffer.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation effects are often used in studios to add depth to sounds.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation changes the perceived spectral structure of a sound but does not alter the pitch.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Basic factors that affect a room's reverberation time include the size and shape of the enclosure as well as the materials used in the construction of the room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Every object placed within the enclosure can also affect this reverberation time, including people and their belongings.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Historically, reverberation time could only be measured using a level recorder (a plotting device which graphs the noise level against time on a ribbon of moving paper).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] A loud noise is produced, and as the sound dies away the trace on the level recorder will show a distinct slope.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Analysis of this slope reveals the measured reverberation time.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Some modern digital sound level meters can carry out this analysis automatically.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Several methods exist for measuring reverberation time.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] An impulse can be measured by creating a sufficiently loud noise (which must have a defined cut-off point).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Impulse noise sources such as a blank pistol shot or balloon burst may be used to measure the impulse response of a room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Alternatively, a random noise signal such as pink noise or white noise may be generated through a loudspeaker, and then turned off.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This is known as the interrupted method, and the measured result is known as the interrupted response.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] A two-port measurement system can also be used to measure noise introduced into a space and compare it to what is subsequently measured in the space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Consider sound reproduced by a loudspeaker into a room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] A recording of the sound in the room can be made and compared to what was sent to the loudspeaker.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The two signals can be compared mathematically.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This two port measurement system uses a Fourier transform to mathematically derive the impulse response of the room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] From the impulse response, the reverberation time can be calculated.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Using a two-port system allows reverberation time to be measured with signals other than loud impulses.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Music or recordings of other sounds can be used.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This allows measurements to be taken in a room after the audience is present.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Reverberation time is usually stated as a decay time and is measured in seconds.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] There may or may not be any statement of the frequency band used in the measurement.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Decay time is the time it takes the signal to diminish 60 dB below the original sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] It is often difficult to inject enough sound into the room to measure a decay of 60 dB, particularly at lower frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] If the decay is linear, it is sufficient to measure a drop of 20 dB and multiply the time by 3, or a drop of 30 dB and multiply the time by 2.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] These are the so-called T20 and T30 measurement methods.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The RT60 reverberation time measurement is defined in the ISO 3382-1 standard for performance spaces, the ISO 3382-2 standard for ordinary rooms, and the ISO 3382-3 for open-plan offices, as well as the ASTM E2235 standard.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The concept of reverberation time implicitly supposes that the decay rate of the sound is exponential, so that the sound level diminishes regularly, at a rate of so many dB per second.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] It is not often the case in real rooms, depending on the disposition of reflective, dispersive and absorbing surfaces.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Moreover, successive measurement of the sound level often yields very different results, as differences in phase in the exciting sound build up in notably different sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Schroeder published "A new method of Measuring Reverberation Time" in the *Journal of the Acoustical Society of America*.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] He proposed to measure, not the power of the sound, but the energy, by integrating it.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This made it possible to show the variation in the rate of decay and to free acousticians from the necessity of averaging many measurements.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Sabine's reverberation equation was developed in the late 1890s in an empirical fashion.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] He established a relationship between the *T*60 of a room, its volume, and its total absorption (in sabins).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] where *c*20 is the speed of sound in the room (at 20 °C), *V* is the volume of the room in m3, *S* total surface area of room in m2, *a* is the average absorption coefficient of room surfaces, and the product *Sa* is the total absorption in sabins.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The total absorption in sabins (and hence reverberation time) generally changes depending on frequency (which is defined by the acoustic properties of the space).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The equation does not take into account room shape or losses from the sound traveling through the air (important in larger spaces).
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Most rooms absorb less sound energy in the lower frequency ranges resulting in longer reverb times at lower frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Sabine concluded that the reverberation time depends upon the reflectivity of sound from various surfaces available inside the hall.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] If the reflection is coherent, the reverberation time of the hall will be longer; the sound will take more time to die out.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] where critical distance $d_{c}$ is measured in meters, volume V is measured in m³, and reverberation time *RT*60 is measured in seconds.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Eyring's reverberation time equation was proposed by Carl F.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This equation aims to better estimate the reverberation time in small rooms with relatively large quantities of sound absorption, identified by Eyring as "dead" rooms.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] These rooms tend to have lower reverberation times than larger, more acoustically live rooms.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Eyring's equation is similar in form to Sabine's equation, but includes modifications to logarithmically scale the absorption term.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The units and variables within the equation are the same as those defined for Sabine's equation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Eyring's equation was developed from first principles using an image source model of sound reflection, as opposed to Sabine's empirical approach.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The experimental results obtained by Sabine generally agree with Eyring's equation since the two formulae become identical for very live rooms, the type in which Sabine worked.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] However, Eyring's equation becomes more valid for smaller rooms with large quantities of absorption.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] As a result, the Eyring equation is often implemented to estimate the reverberation time in recording studio control rooms or other critical listening environments with high quantities of sound absorption.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The Sabine equation tends to over-predict reverberation time for small rooms with high amounts of absorption.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] For this reason, reverberation time calculators available for smaller recording studio environments, such as home recording studios, often use Eyring's equation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The absorption coefficient of a material is a number between 0 and 1 which indicates the proportion of sound which is absorbed by the surface compared to the proportion which is reflected back to the room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] A large, fully open window would offer no reflection as any sound reaching it would pass straight out and no sound would be reflected.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] This would have an absorption coefficient of 1.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Conversely, a thick, smooth painted concrete ceiling would be the acoustic equivalent of a mirror and have an absorption coefficient very close to 0.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Absorption coefficients are frequency-dependent and are typically reported at the standard octave band centre frequencies of 125, 250, 500, 1000, 2000, and 4000 Hz.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] A single-number rating called the weighted sound absorption coefficient (*α*w) can be derived from the frequency-dependent values according to ISO 11654.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] The standard laboratory method for measuring absorption coefficients is ISO 354, which uses a reverberation room and determines the random-incidence absorption coefficient from the change in reverberation time after placing a test specimen in the room.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] An alternative method using an impedance tube (ISO 10534-2) measures the normal-incidence absorption coefficient for small material samples.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Values measured in a reverberation room can exceed 1.0 because edge diffraction effects increase the effective absorbing area beyond the physical dimensions of the specimen.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Gregorian chant may have developed in response to the long reverberation time of cathedrals, limiting the number of notes that could be sung before blending chaotically.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] Artificial reverberation is applied to sound using reverb effects.
[src:spatial-audio-games/reverberation] These simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The sound localization mechanisms of the mammalian auditory system have been extensively studied.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The auditory system uses several cues for sound source localization, including time difference and level difference (or intensity difference) between the ears, and spectral information.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Other animals, such as birds and reptiles, also use them but they may use them differently, and some also have localization cues which are absent in the human auditory system, such as the effects of ear movements.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Animals with the ability to localize sound have an evolutionary advantage.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Sound is the perceptual result of mechanical vibrations traveling through a medium such as air or water.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Through the mechanisms of compression and rarefaction, sound waves travel through the air, bounce off the pinna and concha of the exterior ear, and enter the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In vertebrates, interaural time differences are known to be calculated in the superior olivary nucleus of the brainstem.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] According to Jeffress, this calculation relies on delay lines: neurons in the superior olive which accept innervation from each ear with different connecting axon lengths.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Some cells are more directly connected to one ear than the other, thus they are specific for a particular interaural time difference.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This theory is equivalent to the mathematical procedure of cross-correlation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, because Jeffress's theory is unable to account for the precedence effect, in which only the first of multiple identical sounds is used to determine the sounds' location (thus avoiding confusion caused by echoes), it cannot be entirely used to explain the response.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Furthermore, a number of recent physiological observations made in the midbrain and brainstem of small mammals have shed considerable doubt on the validity of Jeffress's original ideas.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Neurons sensitive to interaural level differences (ILDs) are excited by stimulation of one ear and inhibited by stimulation of the other ear, such that the response magnitude of the cell depends on the relative strengths of the two inputs, which in turn, depends on the sound intensities at the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In the auditory midbrain nucleus, the inferior colliculus (IC), many ILD sensitive neurons have response functions that decline steeply from maximum to zero spikes as a function of ILD.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, there are also many neurons with much more shallow response functions that do not decline to zero spikes.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Sound localization is the process of determining the location of a sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The brain utilizes subtle differences in intensity, spectral, and timing cues to localize sound sources.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Localization can be described in terms of three-dimensional position: the azimuth or horizontal angle, the elevation or vertical angle, and the distance (for static sounds) or velocity (for moving sounds).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The azimuth of a sound is signaled by the difference in arrival times between the ears, by the relative amplitude of high-frequency sounds (the shadow effect), and by the asymmetrical spectral reflections from various parts of our bodies, including torso, shoulders, and pinnae.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The distance cues are the loss of amplitude, the loss of high frequencies, and the ratio of the direct signal to the reverberated signal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Depending on where the source is located, our head acts as a barrier to change the timbre, intensity, and spectral qualities of the sound, helping the brain orient where the sound emanated from.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] These minute differences between the two ears are known as interaural cues.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Lower frequencies, with longer wavelengths, diffract the sound around the head forcing the brain to focus only on the phasing cues from the source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Helmut Haas discovered that we can discern the sound source despite additional reflections at 10 decibels louder than the original wave front, using the earliest arriving wave front.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This principle is known as the Haas effect, a specific version of the precedence effect.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Haas measured down to even a 1 millisecond difference in timing between the original sound and reflected sound increased the spaciousness, allowing the brain to discern the true location of the original sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The nervous system combines all early reflections into a single perceptual whole allowing the brain to process multiple different sounds at once.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The nervous system will combine reflections that are within about 35 milliseconds of each other and that have a similar intensity.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In 1907, Lord Rayleigh utilized tuning forks to generate monophonic excitation and studied the lateral sound localization theory on a human head model without auricle.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] He first presented the interaural clue difference based sound localization theory, which is known as Duplex Theory.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Human ears are on different sides of the head, and thus have different coordinates in space.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As shown in the duplex theory figure, since the distances between the acoustic source and ears are different, there are time difference and intensity difference between the sound signals of two ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] We call those kinds of differences as Interaural Time Difference (ITD) and Interaural Intensity Difference (IID) respectively.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] (ITD) between left ear (top) and right ear (bottom).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] (ILD) between left ear (left) and right ear (right).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] From the duplex theory figure we can see that for source B1 or source B2, there will be a propagation delay between two ears, which will generate the ITD.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Simultaneously, human head and ears may have a shadowing effect on high-frequency signals, which will generate IID.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For frequencies below 800 Hz, the dimensions of the head (ear distance 21.5 cm, corresponding to an interaural time delay of 626 μs) are smaller than the half wavelength of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] So the auditory system can determine phase delays between both ears without confusion.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Interaural level differences are very low in this frequency range, especially below about 200 Hz, so a precise evaluation of the input direction is nearly impossible on the basis of level differences alone.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As the frequency drops below 80 Hz it becomes difficult or impossible to use either time difference or level difference to determine a sound's lateral source, because the phase difference between the ears becomes too small for a directional evaluation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For frequencies above 1600 Hz the dimensions of the head are greater than the length of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] An unambiguous determination of the input direction based on interaural phase alone is not possible at these frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, the interaural level differences become larger, and these level differences are evaluated by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This mechanism becomes especially important in reverberant environments.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] After a sound onset there is a short time frame where the direct sound reaches the ears, but not yet the reflected sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The auditory system uses this short time frame for evaluating the sound source direction, and keeps this detected direction as long as reflections and reverberation prevent an unambiguous direction estimation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The mechanisms described above cannot be used to differentiate between a sound source ahead of the hearer or behind the hearer; therefore additional cues have to be evaluated.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Duplex theory shows that ITD and IID play significant roles in sound localization, but they can only deal with lateral localization problems.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For example, if two acoustic sources are placed symmetrically at the front and back of the right side of the human head, they will generate equal ITDs and IIDs, in what is called the cone model effect.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, human ears can still distinguish between these sources.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Besides that, in natural sense of hearing, one ear alone, without any ITD or IID, can distinguish between them with high accuracy.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Due to the disadvantages of duplex theory, researchers proposed the pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The shape of the human pinna is concave with complex folds and asymmetrical both horizontally and vertically.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Reflected and direct waves generate a frequency spectrum on the eardrum, relating to the acoustic sources.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Then auditory nerves localize the sources using this frequency spectrum.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] These spectrum clues generated by the pinna filtering effect can be presented as a head-related transfer function (HRTF).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The corresponding time domain expressions are called the head-related impulse response (HRIR).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The HRTF is also described as the transfer function from the free field to a specific point in the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] where L and R represent the left ear and right ear respectively, $P_{L}$ and $P_{R}$ represent the amplitude of the sound pressure at the entrances to the left and right ear canals, and $P_{0}$ is the amplitude of sound pressure at the center of the head coordinate when listener does not exist.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In general, an HRTF's $H_{L}$ and $H_{R}$ are functions of source angular position $\theta$ , elevation angle $\varphi$ , the distance between the source and the center of the head r , the angular velocity $\omega$ and the equivalent dimension of the head $\alpha$ .
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] At present, the main institutes that work on measuring HRTF database include CIPIC International Lab, MIT Media Lab, the Graduate School in Psychoacoustics at the University of Oldenburg, the Neurophysiology Lab at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and Ames Lab of NASA.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Databases of HRIRs from humans with normal and impaired hearing and from animals are publicly available.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The human outer ear, i.e. the structures of the pinna and the external ear canal, form direction-selective filters.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Depending on the sound input direction, different filter resonances become active.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] These resonances implant direction-specific patterns into the frequency responses of the ears, which can be evaluated by the auditory system for sound localization.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Together with other direction-selective reflections at the head, shoulders and torso, they form the outer ear transfer functions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] These patterns in the ear's frequency responses are highly individual, depending on the shape and size of the outer ear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] If sound is presented through headphones, and has been recorded via another head with different-shaped outer ear surfaces, the directional patterns differ from the listener's own, and problems will appear when trying to evaluate directions in the median plane with these foreign ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As a consequence, front–back permutations or inside-the-head-localization can appear when listening to dummy head recordings, or otherwise referred to as binaural recordings.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] It has been shown that human subjects can monaurally localize high frequency sound but not low frequency sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Binaural localization, however, was possible with lower frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This is likely due to the pinna being small enough to only interact with sound waves of high frequency.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] It seems that people can only accurately localize the elevation of sounds that are complex and include frequencies above 7,000 Hz, and a pinna must be present.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] When the head is stationary, the binaural cues for lateral sound localization (interaural time difference and interaural level difference) do not give information about the location of a sound in the median plane.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Identical ITDs and ILDs can be produced by sounds at eye level or at any elevation, as long as the lateral direction is constant.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, if the head is rotated, the ITD and ILD change dynamically, and those changes are different for sounds at different elevations.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For example, if an eye-level sound source is straight ahead and the head turns to the left, the sound becomes louder (and arrives sooner) at the right ear than at the left.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] But if the sound source is directly overhead, there will be no change in the ITD and ILD as the head turns.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Intermediate elevations will produce intermediate degrees of change, and if the presentation of binaural cues to the two ears during head movement is reversed, the sound will be heard behind the listener.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Hans Wallach artificially altered a sound's binaural cues during movements of the head.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Although the sound was objectively placed at eye level, the dynamic changes to ITD and ILD as the head rotated were those that would be produced if the sound source had been elevated.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In this situation, the sound was heard at the synthesized elevation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The fact that the sound sources objectively remained at eye level prevented monaural cues from specifying the elevation, showing that it was the dynamic change in the binaural cues during head movement that allowed the sound to be correctly localized in the vertical dimension.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The head movements need not be actively produced; accurate vertical localization occurred in a similar setup when the head rotation was produced passively, by seating the blindfolded subject in a rotating chair.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As long as the dynamic changes in binaural cues accompanied a perceived head rotation, the synthesized elevation was perceived.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In the 1960s Batteau showed the pinna also enhances horizontal localization.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The human auditory system has only limited possibilities to determine the distance of a sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In the close-up-range there are some indications for distance determination, such as extreme level differences (e.g. when whispering into one ear) or specific pinna (the visible part of the ear) resonances in the close-up range.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Sound processing of the human auditory system is performed in so-called critical bands.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The hearing range is segmented into 24 critical bands, each with a width of 1 Bark or 100 Mel.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For a directional analysis the signals inside the critical band are analyzed together.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The auditory system can extract the sound of a desired sound source out of interfering noise.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This allows the listener to concentrate on only one speaker if other speakers are also talking (the cocktail party effect).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] With the help of the cocktail party effect sound from interfering directions is perceived attenuated compared to the sound from the desired direction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The auditory system can increase the signal-to-noise ratio by up to 15 dB, which means that interfering sound is perceived to be attenuated to half (or less) of its actual loudness.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In enclosed rooms not only the direct sound from a sound source is arriving at the listener's ears, but also sound which has been reflected at the walls.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The auditory system analyses only the direct sound, which is arriving first, for sound localization, but not the reflected sound, which is arriving later (law of the first wave front).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] So sound localization remains possible even in an echoic environment.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This echo cancellation occurs in the Dorsal Nucleus of the Lateral Lemniscus (DNLL).
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In order to determine the time periods, where the direct sound prevails and which can be used for directional evaluation, the auditory system analyzes loudness changes in different critical bands and also the stability of the perceived direction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] If there is a strong attack of the loudness in several critical bands and if the perceived direction is stable, this attack is in all probability caused by the direct sound of a sound source, which is entering newly or which is changing its signal characteristics.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This short time period is used by the auditory system for directional and loudness analysis of this sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] When reflections arrive a little bit later, they do not enhance the loudness inside the critical bands in such a strong way, but the directional cues become unstable, because there is a mix of sound of several reflection directions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As a result, no new directional analysis is triggered by the auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This first detected direction from the direct sound is taken as the found sound source direction, until other strong loudness attacks, combined with stable directional information, indicate that a new directional analysis is possible.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This kind of sound localization technique provides us the real virtual stereo system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] It utilizes "smart" manikins, such as KEMAR, to glean signals or use DSP methods to simulate the transmission process from sources to ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] After amplifying, recording and transmitting, the two channels of received signals will be reproduced through earphones or speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This localization approach uses electroacoustic methods to obtain the spatial information of the original sound field by transferring the listener's auditory apparatus to the original sound field.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The most considerable advantages of it would be that its acoustic images are lively and natural.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Also, it only needs two independent transmitted signals to reproduce the acoustic image of a 3D system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The representatives of this kind of system are SRS Audio Sandbox, Spatializer Audio Lab and Qsound Qxpander.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] They use HRTF to simulate the received acoustic signals at the ears from different directions with common binary-channel stereo reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Therefore, they can simulate reflected sound waves and improve subjective sense of space and envelopment.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Since they are para-virtualization stereo systems, the major goal of them is to simulate stereo sound information.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Traditional stereo systems use sensors that are quite different from human ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Although those sensors can receive the acoustic information from different directions, they do not have the same frequency response of human auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Therefore, when binary-channel mode is applied, human auditory systems still cannot feel the 3D sound effect field.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] However, the 3D para-virtualization stereo system overcome such disadvantages.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] It uses HRTF principles to glean acoustic information from the original sound field then produce a lively 3D sound field through common earphones or speakers.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Since the multichannel stereo systems require many reproduction channels, some researchers adopted the HRTF simulation technologies to reduce the number of reproduction channels.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] They use only two speakers to simulate multiple speakers in a multichannel system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This process is called as virtual reproduction.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Essentially, such approach uses both interaural difference principle and pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Unfortunately, this kind of approach cannot perfectly substitute the traditional multichannel stereo system, such as 5.1/7.1 surround sound system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] That is because when the listening zone is relatively larger, simulation reproduction through HRTFs may cause invert acoustic images at symmetric positions.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Since most animals have two ears, many of the effects of the human auditory system can also be found in other animals.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Therefore, interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) and interaural level differences play a role for the hearing of many animals.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] But the influences on localization of these effects are dependent on head sizes, ear distances, the ear positions and the orientation of the ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Smaller animals like insects use different techniques as the separation of the ears are too small.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For the process of animals emitting sound to improve localization, a biological form of active sonar, see animal echolocation.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, similar lateral localization cues as for the human auditory system can be used.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This means: evaluation of interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) for lower frequencies and evaluation of interaural level differences for higher frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The evaluation of interaural phase differences is useful, as long as it gives unambiguous results.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This is the case, as long as ear distance is smaller than half the length (maximal one wavelength) of the sound waves.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For animals with a larger head than humans the evaluation range for interaural phase differences is shifted towards lower frequencies, for animals with a smaller head, this range is shifted towards higher frequencies.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The lowest frequency which can be localized depends on the ear distance.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Animals with a greater ear distance can localize lower frequencies than humans can.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For animals with a smaller ear distance the lowest localizable frequency is higher than for humans.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, interaural level differences appear for higher frequencies and can be evaluated for localization tasks.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For animals with ears at the top of the head, no shadowing by the head will appear and therefore there will be much less interaural level differences which could be evaluated.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Many of these animals can move their ears, and these ear movements can be used as a lateral localization cue.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For many mammals there are also pronounced structures in the pinna near the entry of the ear canal.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] As a consequence, direction-dependent resonances can appear, which could be used as an additional localization cue, similar to the localization in the median plane in the human auditory system.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] There are additional localization cues which are also used by animals.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For sound localization in the median plane (elevation of the sound) also two detectors can be used, which are positioned at different heights.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In animals, however, rough elevation information is gained simply by tilting the head, provided that the sound lasts long enough to complete the movement.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This explains the innate behavior of cocking the head to one side when trying to localize a sound precisely.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] To get instantaneous localization in more than two dimensions from time-difference or amplitude-difference cues requires more than two detectors.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The tiny parasitic fly *Ormia ochracea* has become a model organism in sound localization experiments because of its unique ear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The animal is too small for the time difference of sound arriving at the two ears to be calculated in the usual way, yet it can determine the direction of sound sources with exquisite precision.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The tympanic membranes of opposite ears are directly connected mechanically, allowing resolution of sub-microsecond time differences and requiring a new neural coding strategy.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Ho showed that the coupled-eardrum system in frogs can produce increased interaural vibration disparities when only small arrival time and sound level differences were available to the animal's head.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Efforts to build directional microphones based on the coupled-eardrum structure are underway.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Most owls are nocturnal or crepuscular birds of prey.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Because they hunt at night, they must rely on non-visual senses.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Experiments by Roger Payne have shown that owls are sensitive to the sounds made by their prey, not the heat or the smell.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] In fact, the sound cues are both necessary and sufficient for localization of mice from a distant location where they are perched.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] For this to work, the owls must be able to accurately localize both the azimuth and the elevation of the sound source.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Dolphins (and other odontocetes) rely on echolocation to aid in detecting, identifying, localizing, and capturing prey.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Dolphins can localize sounds both passively and actively (echolocation) with a resolution of about 1 deg.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Cross-modal matching (between vision and echolocation) suggests dolphins perceive the spatial structure of complex objects interrogated through echolocation, a feat that likely requires spatially resolving individual object features and integration into a holistic representation of object shape.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Although dolphins are sensitive to small, binaural intensity and time differences, mounting evidence suggests dolphins employ position-dependent spectral cues derived from well-developed head-related transfer functions, for sound localization in both the horizontal and vertical planes.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] A very small temporal integration time (264 μs) allows localization of multiple targets at varying distances.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Localization adaptations include pronounced asymmetry of the skull, nasal sacks, and specialized lipid structures in the forehead and jaws, as well as acoustically isolated middle and inner ears.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] The term 'binaural' literally signifies 'to hear with two ears', and was introduced in 1859 to signify the practice of listening to the same sound through both ears, or to two discrete sounds, one through each ear.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] It was not until 1916 that Carl Stumpf (1848–1936), a German philosopher and psychologist, distinguished between dichotic listening, which refers to the stimulation of each ear with a different stimulus, and diotic listening, the simultaneous stimulation of both ears with the same stimulus.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Later, it would become apparent that binaural hearing, whether dichotic or diotic, is the means by which sound localization occurs.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Scientific consideration of binaural hearing began before the phenomenon was so named, with speculations published in 1792 by William Charles Wells (1757–1817) based on his research into binocular vision.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Giovanni Battista Venturi (1746–1822) conducted and described experiments in which people tried to localize a sound using both ears, or one ear blocked with a finger.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] This work was not followed up on, and was only recovered after others had worked out how human sound localization works.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Lord Rayleigh (1842–1919) would do these same experiments and come to the results, without knowing Venturi had first done them, almost seventy-five years later.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Charles Wheatstone (1802–1875) did work on optics and color mixing, and also explored hearing.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] He invented a device he called a "microphone" that involved a metal plate over each ear, each connected to metal rods; he used this device to amplify sound.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] He also did experiments holding tuning forks to both ears at the same time, or separately, trying to work out how sense of hearing works, that he published in 1827.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Ernst Heinrich Weber (1795–1878) and August Seebeck (1805–1849) and William Charles Wells also attempted to compare and contrast what would become known as binaural hearing with the principles of binocular integration generally.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Understanding how the differences in sound signals between two ears contributes to auditory processing in such a way as to enable sound localization and direction was considerably advanced after the invention of the stethophone by Somerville Scott Alison in 1859, who coined the term 'binaural'.
[src:spatial-audio-games/sound-localization] Alison based the stethophone on the stethoscope, which had been invented by René Théophile Hyacinthe Laennec (1781–1826); the stethophone had two separate "pickups", allowing the user to hear and compare sounds derived from two discrete locations.
